'''Maxime Crépeau''' (born May 11, 1994) is a Canadian professional [[association football|soccer]] player who plays as a [[goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for [[Major League Soccer]] club [[Orlando City SC|Orlando City]] and the [[Canadian men's national soccer team|Canada national team]].

Crépeau is a product of the [[CF Montréal Academy|Montreal Impact Academy]], and signed with the [[CF Montréal|Montreal Impact]] first team in 2013. Crépeau has since signed with [[FC Montreal]] and [[Ottawa Fury FC|Ottawa Fury]] on loan, and joined the [[Vancouver Whitecaps FC|Vancouver Whitecaps]], [[Los Angeles FC]], [[Portland Timbers]], and Orlando City on permanent contracts. With Los Angeles FC, Crépeau won the 2022 [[Supporters' Shield]] and [[MLS Cup 2022|2022 MLS Cup]].

On the international level, Crépeau played for [[Canada men's national under-17 soccer team|Canada U17]], [[Canada men's national under-20 soccer team|Canada U20]], and [[Canada men's national under-23 soccer team|Canada U23]] teams, before first representing the senior team in 2016. With the senior team, Crépeau has represented Canada at the [[2017 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2017]], [[2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2019]], [[2021 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2021]], and [[2025 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2025]] editions of the [[CONCACAF Gold Cup]] and the [[2024 Copa América]], and will represent Canada at the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].

==Club career==
[[File:Maxime Crépeau 2013.jpg|thumb|Crépeau with [[CF Montréal|Montreal Impact]] in 2013]]

===Montreal Impact===
Crépeau joined the [[CF Montréal Academy|Montreal Impact Academy]] of the [[Canadian Soccer League]] in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.impactmontreal.com/en/players/maxime-cr%C3%A9peau|title=Maxime Crépeau|access-date=January 2, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://canadiansoccerleague.com/teams/team.asp?ID=6|title=Canadian Soccer League|date=February 28, 2011|access-date=September 3, 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110228074855/http://canadiansoccerleague.com/teams/team.asp?ID=6|archive-date=February 28, 2011}}</ref> After three seasons with the U21 squad he signed a senior contract with the [[Montreal Impact (MLS)|Montreal Impact]], becoming the team's fourth [[Homegrown Player Rule (Major League Soccer)|Homegrown Player]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Impact signs Quebec goalkeeper Maxime Crépeau as homegrown player|url=http://www.impactmontreal.com/en/news/2013/03/quebec-goalkeeper-maxime-crepeau-makes-jump-mls-academy|date=March 5, 2013}}</ref> on a four-year contract.<ref name="Dreams">{{cite news|first=Sylvain|last=LaMarre|date=March 25, 2015|title="Il faut persévérer et croire en ses rêves" – Maxime Crépeau|trans-title="We must persevere and believe in your dreams" – Maxime Crépeau|url=http://www.courrierlaval.com/Sports/2015-03-25/article-4089496/%26laquo%3BIl-faut-perseverer-et-croire-en-ses-reves%26raquo%3B---Maxime-Crepeau/1|language=French|newspaper=Courrier Laval|access-date=April 26, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304091746/http://www.courrierlaval.com/Sports/2015-03-25/article-4089496/%26laquo%3BIl-faut-perseverer-et-croire-en-ses-reves%26raquo%3B---Maxime-Crepeau/1|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> On January 5, 2015, Crépeau joined German club [[Fortuna Düsseldorf]] for a ten-day training stint before the open of Montreal's pre-season camp for the [[2015 MLS season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-ca/news/4175/major-league-soccer/2014/12/22/7322382/montreal-impact-goalkeeper-maxime-cr%C3%A9peau-to-train-with|first=Nick|last=Sabetti|title=Montreal Impact goalkeeper Maxime Crépeau to train with Fortuna Düsseldorf|website=Goal|date=December 22, 2014}}</ref> After spending the beginning of the [[2015 Montreal Impact season|2015 season]] with the Impact, Crépeau sat on the bench as the backup goalkeeper during the second leg of the [[2015 CONCACAF Champions League Finals]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Nick|last=Sabetti|title=Montreal Impact face potential goalkeeper emergency ahead of Champions League final return leg|url=http://www.goal.com/en-ca/news/4186/concacaf-champions-league/2015/04/25/11080792/montreal-impact-face-potential-goalkeeper-emergency-ahead-of|website=Goal|date=April 25, 2015|access-date=April 26, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.concacaf.com/category/champions-league/game-detail/203223|title=Champions League|publisher=[[CONCACAF]]|date=April 29, 2015|access-date=May 2, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728081232/http://www.concacaf.com/category/champions-league/game-detail/203223|archive-date=July 28, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>

After the match, as originally planned,<ref name="Dreams"/> Crépeau was loaned to [[FC Montreal]], the Impact's [[United Soccer League|USL]] affiliate team, making his professional debut against the [[Rochester Rhinos]] on May 2, 2015.<ref>{{cite tweet|author=FC Montreal|author-link=FC Montreal|user=fcmontrealusl|number= 594585499148353536|date=May 2, 2015|title=XI partant du #FCMTL face aux @RochesterRhinos. Coup d'envoi à 16h00.|access-date=May 2, 2015|language=French}}</ref> Crépeau would spend two seasons with FC Montreal before the club ceased operations after the 2016 season.

Prior to the [[2017 Montreal Impact season|2017 season]], the Impact promoted Crépeau to the backup goalkeeper position, behind [[Evan Bush]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/local-news/young-impact-goalkeeper-maxime-crepeau-moves-up-to-no-2-aims-higher|title=Young Impact goalkeeper Maxime Crépeau moves up to No. 2, aims higher|author=Neil Davidson|publisher=Montreal Gazette|date=February 21, 2017}}</ref> In May 2017, Crépeau made his first-team debut in the first leg of the [[2017 Canadian Championship]] against [[Vancouver Whitecaps FC|Vancouver Whitecaps]].<ref>{{cite tweet|author=Montreal Impact|author-link=CF Montreal|user=impactmontreal|number=867195634343829504|date=May 23, 2017|title=If you didn't notice, @MaxCrepeau makes his first competitive start with #IMFC. Good luck Max! #CanChamp}}</ref>

====Loan to Ottawa Fury====
Citing a desire for more playing time in 2018, Crépeau was loaned to the [[Ottawa Fury FC|Ottawa Fury]] of the [[United Soccer League|USL]] for the [[2018 Ottawa Fury FC season|2018 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.impactmontreal.com/en/post/2018/01/21/maxime-cr%C3%A9peau-loaned-ottawa-fury-fc-2018-season|title=Maxime Crépeau loaned to Ottawa Fury FC for the 2018 season|website=Montreal Impact|date=January 21, 2018}}</ref> After not conceding a goal in six straight games, Crépeau was named USL Player of the Month for May 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ottawafuryfc.com/news_article/show/927065|title=Goalkeeper Crépeau voted player of the month|website=Ottawa Fury|date=June 15, 2018}}</ref> While playing every game for the Fury, he would consider his time with the club as a renewal, allowing him to improve on aspects of his game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ottawasports.ca/five-guys-one-couch-a-profile-of-fury-fcs-maxime-crepeau/|title=Five Guys One Couch - A profile of Fury FC's Maxime Crépeau|website=Ottawa Sports Network|author=Theo Gauthier|date=July 18, 2018|access-date=July 18, 2018|archive-date=July 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719000135/http://www.ottawasports.ca/five-guys-one-couch-a-profile-of-fury-fcs-maxime-crepeau/|url-status=dead}}</ref> By the close of the season Crépeau had set a new USL record for the most shutouts in a single season with 15, surpassing [[Brandon Miller (soccer)|Brandon Miller]] who at the time was playing for the [[Rochester Rhinos]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ottawafuryfc.com/news_article/show/953660|title=Maxime Crépeau sets a new USL record for the most shutouts in a single season|last=FC|first=Ottawa Fury|date=September 26, 2018|work=Ottawa Fury|access-date=October 1, 2018|language=en-us}}</ref> Crépeau would be named to the USL's All-League First Team, and would also be named USL Goalkeeper of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ottawafuryfc.com/news_article/show/965629?platform=hootsuite|title=Fury FC goalkeeper Maxime Crepeau selected on USL All-League First Team|website=Ottawa Fury FC|date=November 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uslsoccer.com/news_article/show/967766|title=Ottawa's Crepeau Claims Goalkeeper of the Year Honor|website=USL|date=November 12, 2018}}</ref> After the 2018 season, the Fury would announce that Crépeau would not return to the Fury for the 2019 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ottawafuryfc.com/news_article/show/961746|title=Fury FC roster moves: five core players to return, 15 players released|website=Ottawa Fury FC|date=October 23, 2018}}</ref>

===Vancouver Whitecaps===
On December 9, 2018, Crépeau was traded to the [[Vancouver Whitecaps FC|Vancouver Whitecaps]] in exchange for $50,000 in Targeted Allocation Money and a third-round pick in the [[2020 MLS SuperDraft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitecapsfc.com/post/2018/12/09/wfc-acquire-crepeau|title=Whitecaps FC acquire Canadian goalkeeper Maxime Crépeau from Montreal Impact|publisher=Vancouver Whitecaps FC|date=December 9, 2018|access-date=December 9, 2018}}</ref> He made his debut in the Whitecaps' season opener on March 2, 2019, against [[Minnesota United]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dailyhive.com/vancouver/whitecaps-fc-mls-season-opener-2019|date=March 2, 2019|title=9 players make Whitecaps debut in MLS season opener|first=Mark|last=Dailey}}</ref> Crepeau took over the starting goalkeeper role with the Whitecaps in 2019 and 2020, but missed a large portion of the 2020 season due to suffering a fractured thumb in the [[MLS is Back Tournament]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2020/07/21/vancouver-whitecaps-fc-goalkeeper-maxime-crepeau-suffers-fractured-thumb|title=Vancouver Whitecaps FC goalkeeper Maxime Crepeau suffers fractured thumb|website=Major League Soccer|date=July 21, 2020}}</ref> In 2019 and 2021, he was named Whitecaps' player of the year.<ref name=ReffyOne/> By early 2022, he had been in 63 league and cup appearances, and 14 international appearances for Canada.<ref name="ReffyTwo">[https://www.espn.com/soccer/soccer-transfers/story/4573998/source-lafc-set-to-sign-vancouver-whitecaps-keeper-maxime-crepeau], "Source: LAFC set to sign Vancouver Whitecaps keeper Maxime Crepeau," Jeff Carlisle, [[ESPN]], January 19, 2022</ref>

===Los Angeles FC===
On January 20, 2022, Crépeau was traded to [[Los Angeles FC]] for $1 million in allocation money.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.whitecapsfc.com/news/whitecaps-fc-acquire-1-million-in-gam-plus-additional-incentives-from-lafc |title= Whitecaps FC acquire $1 million in GAM plus additional incentives from LAFC in exchange for goalkeeper Maxime Crépeau | website=Whitecaps FC|date=January 20, 2022}}</ref> Concerning the reasons for the move, Whitecaps CEO Axel Schuster did not give details but cited a "very special personal situation." Crepeau called the decision "personally the hardest decision I've had to make in my professional career," and noted it was not due to health of him or his family. He joined [[Tomas Romero (footballer)|Tomas Romero]] and [[John McCarthy (soccer)|John McCarthy]] at LAFC as the team keepers.<ref name="ReffyOne">[https://www.winnipegfreepress.com/sports/soccer/traded-to-lafc-former-caps-goalkeeper-maxime-crepeau-still-on-the-move-with-canada-576119642.html], "Traded to LAFC, former 'Caps goalkeeper Maxime Crepeau still on the move with Canada," Neil Davidson, ''[[Winnipeg Free Press]]'', January 25, 2022</ref> He made his debut for Los Angeles on February 26 in their season-opener against the [[Colorado Rapids]], keeping a clean-sheet in a 3–0 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lafc.com/news/carlos-vela-hat-trick-helps-lafc-earn-3-0-win-over-colorado-in-2022-mls-season-o|title=Carlos Vela Hat Trick Helps LAFC Earn 3-0 Win Over Colorado In 2022 MLS Season Opener|date=February 26, 2022}}</ref> Crépeau started all but one game for LAFC in the 2022 season, but suffered a serious leg injury while drawing a red card in extra time of the [[MLS Cup 2022|2022 MLS Cup]] in an attempt to defend a [[Philadelphia Union]] breakaway caused by an errant back pass, a game from which Los Angeles would emerge victorious on penalties.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ca.sports.yahoo.com/news/world-cup-canadian-goalie-maxime-crepeau-carted-off-with-scary-injury-in-mls-cup-235523690.html|title=Canadian goalie Maxime Crépeau carted off with scary injury in MLS Cup|website=Yahoo Sports|date=November 5, 2022}}</ref>

Crépeau made his return to the pitch on July 23, 2023, with [[MLS Next Pro]] side [[Los Angeles FC 2]], starting and captaining the team to a 2–1 victory over the [[Tacoma Defiance]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlsnextpro.com/news/mls-next-pro-matchday-18-recap-blitz|date=July 23, 2023|title=MLS NEXT Pro Matchday 18: Recap Blitz|work=[[MLS Next Pro]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|author=[[Sportsnet]]|user=Sportsnet|number=1683473759678734342|title=260 days after suffering a broken leg in the 2022 MLS Cup Final, Canadian goalkeeper Maxime Crépeau made his return to the pitch with LAFC II.|date=July 24, 2023|access-date=July 24, 2023}}</ref>

===Portland Timbers===
Crépeau joined the [[Portland Timbers]] on January 17, 2024, through the 2025 season with a club option for 2026.<ref>{{cite web |title=Timbers sign goalkeeper Maxime Crépeau |url=https://www.timbers.com/news/timbers-sign-goalkeeper-maxime-crepeau |website=[[Portland Timbers]] |access-date=17 January 2024}}</ref> He made his debut for Portland on March 2 against [[D.C. United]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timbers.com/news/portland-timbers-draw-2-2-with-d-c-united|title=RECAP - Portland Timbers draw 2-2 with D.C. United|date=March 3, 2023|work=[[Portland Timbers]]}}</ref> On July 25, 2025, Crépeau made a save on a [[bicycle kick]] shot from [[Kenny Nielsen]] in a 1–0 win at Los Angeles FC.<ref>{{Cite web |date=July 26, 2025 |title=RECAP {{!}} Portland Timbers smash and grab a 1-0 road win over LAFC |url=https://www.timbers.com/news/recap-portland-timbers-smash-and-grab-a-1-0-road-win-over-lafc |access-date=January 6, 2026 |website=[[Portland Timbers]]}}</ref> This save would become a finalist for the 2025 [[MLS Save of the Year Award|Save of the Year]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=October 20, 2025 |title=Vote Maxime Crépeau for 2025 MLS Save of the Year |url=https://www.timbers.com/news/vote-maxime-crepeau-for-2025-mls-save-of-the-year |access-date=January 6, 2026 |website=[[Portland Timbers]]}}</ref> On November 14, the Timbers announced that he would leave the team upon the expiration of his contract.<ref>{{Cite web |date=November 14, 2025 |title=Timbers announce roster status ahead of 2026 MLS season |url=https://www.timbers.com/news/timbers-announce-roster-status-ahead-of-2026-mls-season |access-date=January 6, 2026 |website=[[Portland Timbers]]}}</ref>

===Orlando City===
On January 6, 2026, Crépeau signed with [[Orlando City SC|Orlando City]], through the 2027–28 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.orlandocitysc.com/news/orlando-city-sc-signs-goalkeeper-maxime-crepeau|title=Orlando City SC signs goalkeeper Maxime Crépeau|date=January 6, 2026|work=[[Orlando City SC]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Gramajo |first=Mike |date=January 6, 2026 |title=Orlando City signs goalkeeper Maxime Crepeau in free agency |url=https://www.wesh.com/article/orlando-city-signs-goalkeeper-maxime-crepeau-free-agency/69700785 |access-date=January 6, 2026 |work=[[WESH]]}}</ref> By signing with Orlando City, Crépeau joined the [[Inter Miami CF–Orlando City SC rivalry|rival team]] of [[Inter Miami CF|Inter Miami]], where fellow Canadian international [[Dayne St. Clair]] had recently signed. At the time of signing, Crépeau and St. Clair were competing for the starting goalkeeper spot for Canada at the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]]. Crépeau said the pair had not intended to sign with rival clubs when they became [[Free agent#Association football|free agents]], but it added a "bit of spice" to their rivalry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.orlandocitysc.com/news/new-lions-goalkeeper-maxime-crepeau-embraces-new-challenge-in-orlando|title=New Lions goalkeeper Maxime Crépeau embraces new challenge in Orlando|date=January 30, 2026|access-date=January 30, 2026|website=[[Orlando City SC|Orlando City]]|last=David|first=Austin}}</ref> Crépeau started in Orlando City's season-opening match against the [[New York Red Bulls]] on February 21, which resulted in a 2–1 loss, but he was credited for making 11 saves, tying [[Mason Stajduhar]]'s team record for the most saves in a single game.<ref>{{Cite news |date=February 21, 2026 |title=Julian Hall, Kevin Horvath lead Red Bulls to 2-0 victory over Orlando City in season opener |url=https://apnews.com/article/new-york-red-bulls-orlando-city-score-mls-d96880dc9e344a4edcdcb36b23f3d220 |access-date=February 21, 2026 |work=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=February 22, 2026 |title=Match report: Orlando City SC drops season opener Against Red Bull New York |url=https://www.orlandocitysc.com/news/match-report-orlando-city-sc-drops-season-opener-against-red-bull-new-york |access-date=February 22, 2026 |website=[[Orlando City SC|Orlando City]]}}</ref> On March 7, early into Crépeau's third appearance for Orlando City, he received a [[Penalty card#Red card|red card]] for handling the ball outside the penalty box against [[New York City FC]]. After Crépeau's expulsion, Orlando City went on to lose 5–0, their [[List of Orlando City SC records and statistics#Team records|joint-worst defeat in their history]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=March 7, 2026 |title=Match report: 10-man Orlando City SC falls 5-0 to New York City FC |url=https://www.orlandocitysc.com/news/match-report-10-man-orlando-city-sc-falls-5-0-to-new-york-city-fc |access-date=March 7, 2026 |website=[[Orlando City SC|Orlando City]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=March 7, 2026 |title=Parks scores twice in second half, New York City FC rolls Orlando City 5-0 |url=https://apnews.com/article/orlando-new-york-soccer-game-2ea3b9634bb8faee34df8d857a7c3feb |access-date=March 7, 2026 |work=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> Crépeau was later fined by the league's disciplinary committee for failing to leave the field in an appropriate amount of time after receiving the red card.<ref>{{Cite web |date=March 10, 2026 |title=Orlando City's Maxime Crépeau fined by MLS Disciplinary Committee |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/orlando-city-s-maxime-crepeau-fined-by-mls-disciplinary-committee |access-date=March 11, 2026 |website=[[Major League Soccer]]}}</ref>

==International career==

===Youth teams===
Crépeau represented Canada at the youth level, participating in the [[2011 CONCACAF U-17 Championship]] and the subsequent [[2011 FIFA U-17 World Cup|FIFA U-17 World Cup]] later that same year. He then went on to represent Canada at the [[2013 CONCACAF U-20 Championship]]. In August 2015 Crépeau was named to the [[2015 Pan American Games]] roster. On September 18, 2015, he was announced as part of the [[2015 CONCACAF Men's Olympic Qualifying Championship]] team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://canadasoccer.com/canada-m23-picks-players-for-concacaf-olympic-qualifiers-p158531|title=Canada M23 picks players for CONCACAF Olympic Qualifiers|date=September 18, 2015|access-date=September 18, 2015|archive-date=September 21, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150921011351/http://canadasoccer.com/canada-m23-picks-players-for-concacaf-olympic-qualifiers-p158531|url-status=dead}}</ref>

In May 2016, Crepeau was called to [[Canada men's national under-23 soccer team|Canada's U23 national team]] for a pair of friendlies against [[Guyana national football team|Guyana]] and [[Grenada national football team|Grenada]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://canadasoccer.com/canada-announces-roster-for-caribbean-tour-p159488|title=Canada announces roster for Caribbean tour|author=Canada Soccer Association|access-date=May 19, 2016|archive-date=June 16, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616202030/http://canadasoccer.com/canada-announces-roster-for-caribbean-tour-p159488|url-status=dead}}</ref> He started the second match against Guyana, posting a 5–1 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://canadasoccer.com/canada-m23-wins-again-on-caribbean-tour-p159531|title=Canada m23 wins again on Caribbean tour|author=Canada Soccer Association|access-date=May 19, 2016|archive-date=June 16, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616195439/http://canadasoccer.com/canada-m23-wins-again-on-caribbean-tour-p159531|url-status=dead}}</ref>
[[File:Maxime Crépeau - ARG v CAN - 2024-07-09 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Crépeau with [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]] in 2024]]

===Senior team===
Crépeau received his first call up to the [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canadian senior team]] in January 2014, as part of a training camp under coach [[Benito Floro]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Young MNT to set up camp in Florida|date=January 10, 2014|url=http://www.canadasoccer.com/young-mnt-to-set-up-camp-in-florida-p155752|access-date=April 15, 2015|archive-date=February 13, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140213235902/http://www.canadasoccer.com/young-mnt-to-set-up-camp-in-florida-p155752|url-status=dead}}</ref> He made his debut against the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] on February 2, 2016. In June 2017 Crépeau was called up to the senior team for the [[2017 CONCACAF Gold Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.canadasoccer.com/canada-selects-dynamic-squad-for-2017-concacaf-gold-cup-p160970|date=June 27, 2017|title=Canada selects dynamic squad for 2017 CONCACAF Gold Cup|access-date=June 17, 2019|archive-date=August 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200803114704/https://www.canadasoccer.com/canada-selects-dynamic-squad-for-2017-concacaf-gold-cup-p160970|url-status=dead}}</ref> He made one appearance at the tournament, replacing an injured [[Milan Borjan]] in Canada's tournament opener against [[French Guiana national football team|French Guiana]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://matchcenter.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter/2017-07-07-french-guiana-vs-canada/recap|date=July 7, 2017|first=Franco|last=Panizo|title=French Guiana 2, Canada 4 - 2017 CONCACAF Gold Cup Match Recap|access-date=June 17, 2019|archive-date=January 23, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210123041421/https://matchcenter.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter/2017-07-07-french-guiana-vs-canada/recap|url-status=dead}}</ref> Crépeau was named to the squad for the [[2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup]] in May 2019,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.canadasoccer.com/together-we-rise-canada-soccer-announces-squad-for-the-2019-concacaf-gold-cup-p162198|date=May 30, 2019|title=Together We Rise: Canada Soccer announces squad for the 2019 Concacaf Gold Cup|publisher=CanadaSoccer.com|access-date=June 17, 2019|archive-date=June 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190603025211/https://www.canadasoccer.com/together-we-rise-canada-soccer-announces-squad-for-the-2019-concacaf-gold-cup-p162198|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the [[2021 CONCACAF Gold Cup]] in July 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.canadasoccer.com/news/canada-soccer-announces-2021-concacaf-gold-cup-roster/|title=Canada Soccer Announces 2021 CONCACAF Gold Cup Roster|publisher=CanadaSoccer.com|date=July 1, 2021}}</ref> In the 2021 Gold Cup, regular Canada starter Borjan was not called up, leaving Crépau as the first choice keeper for the tournament. He played all of Canada's matches as the team advanced all the way to the semifinals before bowing out against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]]. It was Canada's best performance at the Gold Cup since [[2007 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2007]].<ref>{{Cite web |author=TSN ca Staff |date=December 23, 2021 |title=2021 in review: Canadian soccer stands tall - TSN.ca |url=https://www.tsn.ca/2021-in-review-canadian-soccer-stands-tall-1.1738493 |access-date=June 14, 2022 |website=TSN |language=en}}</ref>

Crépeau was a regular call-up during the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification – CONCACAF third round|final round]] of qualification for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]], and featured in the October 2021 window against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]], [[Jamaica national football team|Jamaica]] and [[Panama national football team|Panama]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitecapsfc.com/news/crepeau-canada-earn-huge-point-in-mexico|title=Crépeau, Canada earn huge point in Mexico|date=October 7, 2022|work=[[Vancouver Whitecaps FC]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitecapsfc.com/news/crepeau-cornelius-help-canmnt-earn-important-point-in-jamaica|title=Crépeau, Cornelius help CANMNT earn important point in Jamaica|date=October 10, 2021|work=[[Vancouver Whitecaps FC]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thesuburban.com/sports/canada-defeats-panama-4-1-in-front-of-26-622-at-bmo-field/article_e7cfa51d-2c39-5ef0-ac3a-ddf799fbc581.html|title=Canada defeats Panama 4:1 in front of 26,622 at BMO Field|date=October 14, 2021|work=The Suburban}}</ref> In November 2022, he suffered a broken lower leg during the [[2022 MLS Cup|MLS Cup Final]], ruling him out of the World Cup squad.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://canadasoccer.com/news/maxime-crepeau-suffers-lower-leg-injury-that-will-keep-him-out-of-the-fifa-world-cup/|title=MAXIME CRÉPEAU SUFFERS LOWER LEG INJURY THAT WILL KEEP HIM OUT OF THE FIFA WORLD CUP|date=November 11, 2022|work=Canada Soccer}}</ref>

In June 2024, Crépeau was named to Canada's squad for the [[2024 Copa América]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://canadasoccer.com/news/canmnt-announce-2024-copa-america-roster/|title=CANMNT ANNOUNCE 2024 COPA AMÉRICA ROSTER|date=June 15, 2024|work= [[Canadian Soccer Association]]}}</ref> In July 2025, he was named to the squad for the [[2025 CONCACAF Gold Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.onesoccer.ca/a/canmnt-announce-2025-conacaf-gold-cup-squad-roster-canada-soccer|date=July 5, 2025|title=CanMNT name full-strength squad for 2025 Concacaf Gold Cup|first=Mitchell|last=Tierney}}</ref> In May 2026, Crépeau was called up to Canada's 26-man squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://northerntribune.ca/world-cup-2026-canada-squad/|first=John|last=Jacques|date=May 29, 2026|title=Here’s The Canada World Cup Roster|work=Northern Tribune}}</ref> On June 4, Canada head coach [[Jesse Marsch]] announced during a press conference in [[Montreal]] that Crépeau would be the starting goalkeeper for Canada during the tournament.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Callaghan |first=Joe |date=June 5, 2026 |title=Canada reveals No. 1 in net for the World Cup before tackling tougher questions in final tuneup |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/soccer/world-cup/canada-reveals-no-1-in-net-for-the-world-cup-before-tackling-tougher-questions-in-final-tuneup/article_ec4db13f-ba8c-4a35-b9e1-03bd31eb184a.html |access-date=June 5, 2026 |work=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref>

